---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
// Use the same main Figma image for the About page background
const bgImage = `${base}images/aurora-bg.jpg`;
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="Everything about the aurora borealis — science, space weather, how to see it, photograph it, and the best places to go."
  bgImage={bgImage}
>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════
       HERO
  ══════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <div class="about-hero">
    <h1 class="hero-title">AURORA BOREALIS</h1>
    <p class="hero-sub">
      Nature's most dramatic light show — caused by charged particles from the Sun
      colliding with Earth's magnetic field. Green curtains at 110 km, crimson arches at 300 km,
      violet fringes from nitrogen — all dancing above the Arctic in silence.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════
       PHOTO GALLERY (free-use Unsplash)
  ══════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="gallery-section">
    <div class="gallery-grid">
      <div class="gallery-item gallery-tall">
        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1531366936337-7c912a4589a7?auto=format&fit=crop&w=700&q=82"
             alt="Green aurora borealis over a still arctic lake" loading="lazy" />
        <div class="gallery-caption">Green aurora reflected in still arctic water</div>
      </div>
      <div class="gallery-right">
        <div class="gallery-item">
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1566132127697-4524fea60007?auto=format&fit=crop&w=600&q=80"
               alt="Aurora borealis over snow-capped mountains" loading="lazy" />
          <div class="gallery-caption">Aurora over snow-capped peaks — Iceland</div>
        </div>
        <div class="gallery-item">
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1551244072-5d12893278bc?auto=format&fit=crop&w=600&q=80"
               alt="Purple and green auroral curtains" loading="lazy" />
          <div class="gallery-caption">Purple and green curtains — Norwegian Lapland</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="gallery-item">
        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1494243762909-b498c7e7b548?auto=format&fit=crop&w=700&q=80"
             alt="Aurora borealis over a remote road" loading="lazy" />
        <div class="gallery-caption">Aurora over a remote Arctic road</div>
      </div>
      <div class="gallery-item">
        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1517649763962-0c623066013b?auto=format&fit=crop&w=700&q=80"
             alt="Aurora in Alaska over mountains" loading="lazy" />
        <div class="gallery-caption">Aurora borealis over Alaskan mountain range</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="gallery-credit">
      Photos: <a href="https://unsplash.com/s/photos/aurora-borealis" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Unsplash</a>
      — free-to-use, no attribution required under Unsplash License
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════
       SCIENCE — HOW AURORAS FORM
  ══════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">HOW THE AURORA FORMS</h2>
    <div class="science-flow">

      <div class="sci-step">
        <div class="sci-step-num">01</div>
        <div class="sci-icon">☀️</div>
        <h3>Solar Wind & CMEs</h3>
        <p>The Sun emits a continuous stream of electrons and protons called the solar wind. During solar flares and coronal mass ejections (CMEs), billions of tons of magnetized plasma are hurled toward Earth at 1–3 million km/h — arriving in 1–4 days.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="sci-arrow">→</div>

      <div class="sci-step">
        <div class="sci-step-num">02</div>
        <div class="sci-icon">🧲</div>
        <h3>Magnetic Reconnection</h3>
        <p>Earth's magnetosphere deflects most solar wind. But when the interplanetary magnetic field (IMF) Bz component turns southward, it connects with Earth's northward field — a process called magnetic reconnection — opening a channel for particles to flow inward.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="sci-arrow">→</div>

      <div class="sci-step">
        <div class="sci-step-num">03</div>
        <div class="sci-icon">⚡</div>
        <h3>Particle Acceleration</h3>
        <p>Charged particles accelerate along magnetic field lines toward the polar regions, guided by Earth's dipole field. This is why aurora concentrates in oval-shaped rings around the geomagnetic poles, typically between 65°–72°N latitude.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="sci-arrow">→</div>

      <div class="sci-step">
        <div class="sci-step-num">04</div>
        <div class="sci-icon">💡</div>
        <h3>Atmospheric Excitation</h3>
        <p>Particles collide with oxygen and nitrogen atoms at 80–300 km altitude. These atoms absorb the energy and re-emit it as visible light. The altitude and gas type determine the color — green from oxygen at 110 km, red above 200 km, blue-violet from nitrogen molecules.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════
       AURORA COLORS GUIDE
  ══════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">WHAT CAUSES EACH COLOR</h2>
    <div class="colors-grid">
      <div class="color-card green-card">
        <div class="color-swatch green-swatch"></div>
        <div class="color-body">
          <h3>Green</h3>
          <div class="color-detail">Oxygen · 100–150 km altitude</div>
          <p>The most common aurora color. Atomic oxygen at ~110 km emits the characteristic 557.7 nm green line. Almost every aurora display shows green — it's the dominant color in the auroral oval.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="color-card red-card">
        <div class="color-swatch red-swatch"></div>
        <div class="color-body">
          <h3>Red</h3>
          <div class="color-detail">Oxygen · 200–300 km altitude</div>
          <p>Rare red aurora appears at high altitude where the atmosphere is thinner. The same oxygen atom at 630 nm emits red — but only when collision frequency is low enough not to quench the emission. Visible during strong storms (Kp 7+).</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="color-card blue-card">
        <div class="color-swatch blue-swatch"></div>
        <div class="color-body">
          <h3>Blue / Violet</h3>
          <div class="color-detail">Nitrogen molecules · 80–100 km</div>
          <p>Ionized nitrogen molecules (N₂⁺) produce blue and violet light at lower altitudes. Often visible at the lower edge of green curtains as a blue fringe. Also creates the purple in mixed displays.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="color-card pink-card">
        <div class="color-swatch pink-swatch"></div>
        <div class="color-body">
          <h3>Pink / Magenta</h3>
          <div class="color-detail">Nitrogen + Oxygen mix · 90–100 km</div>
          <p>Pink aurora appears when nitrogen emissions at the lower edge of a green aurora layer blend together. Often forms the lowest, brightest portions of active aurora curtains during substorm events.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="color-card white-card">
        <div class="color-swatch white-swatch"></div>
        <div class="color-body">
          <h3>White / Yellow</h3>
          <div class="color-detail">Mixed green + red + blue</div>
          <p>When aurora is very bright and intense, the eye's color receptors saturate and the mixed light appears white or yellowish. Also common in fast-moving, structureless "veil" aurora during substorm onset.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="color-card steve-card">
        <div class="color-swatch steve-swatch"></div>
        <div class="color-body">
          <h3>STEVE (Mauve)</h3>
          <div class="color-detail">Sub-Auroral Ion Drift · 100–130 km</div>
          <p>Strong Thermal Emission Velocity Enhancement — a narrow, mauve-colored arc running east-west, distinct from traditional aurora. Discovered by citizen scientists in 2016. Caused by a hot, fast plasma stream, not by particle precipitation.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════
       KP INDEX & BZ — HOW TO READ THEM
  ══════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">READING SPACE WEATHER DATA</h2>
    <div class="reading-grid">

      <div class="reading-card card">
        <h3 class="reading-title">The Kp Index</h3>
        <p class="reading-intro">The Planetary K-index (Kp) is the primary metric for geomagnetic activity, measured globally on a scale of 0–9. Updated every 3 hours by NOAA.</p>
        <div class="kp-scale-visual">
          {[
            {kp:0, label:'Quiet', color:'#39ff8a', desc:'No aurora'},
            {kp:1, label:'Quiet', color:'#5dfa7a', desc:'Polar regions only'},
            {kp:2, label:'Quiet', color:'#8df55c', desc:'70°N+'},
            {kp:3, label:'Unsettled', color:'#c8f042', desc:'65°N+ — Iceland, Norway'},
            {kp:4, label:'Active', color:'#fbbf24', desc:'60°N+ — Scotland, Canada'},
            {kp:5, label:'Minor G1', color:'#f97316', desc:'55°N+ — Northern US'},
            {kp:6, label:'Moderate G2', color:'#f05, 50%', desc:'50°N+ — N. Germany'},
            {kp:7, label:'Strong G3', color:'#ef4444', desc:'45°N+ — Central Europe'},
            {kp:8, label:'Severe G4', color:'#dc2626', desc:'40°N+ — Southern Europe'},
            {kp:9, label:'Extreme G5', color:'#b91c1c', desc:'35°N+ — Major storm'},
          ].map(({kp, label, desc}) => (
            <div class="kp-scale-row">
              <span class={`kps-badge kps-${kp}`}>Kp {kp}</span>
              <span class="kps-desc">{desc}</span>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
        <p class="reading-note">Kp 5+ triggers the G-scale (G1–G5). The May 2024 storm reached Kp 9 — aurora was visible as far south as Florida and Texas.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="reading-card card">
        <h3 class="reading-title">The Bz Component</h3>
        <p class="reading-intro">Bz is the north-south component of the interplanetary magnetic field (IMF). It's the single most important real-time indicator for aurora.</p>
        <div class="bz-explainer">
          <div class="bz-ex-item bz-south-ex">
            <div class="bz-ex-icon">▼</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Southward Bz (negative)</strong>
              <p>When Bz points south (negative values), the IMF connects with Earth's field via magnetic reconnection. Solar particles stream into the magnetosphere. Aurora intensifies. The more negative Bz is, the better — values of −20 nT or below indicate major storm conditions.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="bz-ex-item bz-north-ex">
            <div class="bz-ex-icon">▲</div>
            <div>
              <strong>Northward Bz (positive)</strong>
              <p>When Bz points north (positive values), Earth's magnetosphere is shielded. Solar particles are deflected away. Aurora is suppressed even during otherwise active conditions. A storm can "turn off" instantly when Bz flips northward.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="bz-tip-box">
          <span class="bz-tip-label">PRO TIP</span>
          <p>Watch for Bz to go strongly negative (−10 nT or lower) and stay that way for 20+ minutes. That sustained southward field drives the best aurora displays. Short dips often don't sustain long enough to cause major activity.</p>
        </div>

        <h3 class="reading-title" style="margin-top:20px">Solar Wind Speed</h3>
        <p class="reading-intro">Solar wind speed affects how fast magnetic disturbances travel. Faster wind = stronger dynamic pressure on the magnetosphere.</p>
        <div class="wind-table">
          <div class="wt-row"><span class="wt-speed">250–350 km/s</span><span class="wt-label">Slow — weak activity even with southward Bz</span></div>
          <div class="wt-row"><span class="wt-speed wt-avg">350–500 km/s</span><span class="wt-label">Average — typical aurora conditions</span></div>
          <div class="wt-row"><span class="wt-speed wt-fast">500–700 km/s</span><span class="wt-label">Fast — enhanced aurora even with moderate Bz</span></div>
          <div class="wt-row"><span class="wt-speed wt-storm">700+ km/s</span><span class="wt-label">Storm-level — associated with CME arrival</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════
       NOAA SPACE WEATHER SCALES
  ══════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">NOAA SPACE WEATHER SCALES</h2>
    <div class="scales-tabs-grid">

      <!-- G Scale -->
      <div class="scale-block card">
        <div class="scale-block-header">
          <span class="scale-letter-big">G</span>
          <div>
            <div class="scale-block-title">Geomagnetic Storms</div>
            <div class="scale-block-sub">Kp-driven · Key aurora metric</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="scale-rows">
          <div class="sr sr-g1"><span class="sr-badge g1">G1</span><span class="sr-kp">Kp 5</span><span class="sr-vis">60°N+</span><span class="sr-fx">Power grid fluctuations, minor satellite drag</span></div>
          <div class="sr sr-g2"><span class="sr-badge g2">G2</span><span class="sr-kp">Kp 6</span><span class="sr-vis">55°N+</span><span class="sr-fx">High-latitude power systems affected, transformer damage possible</span></div>
          <div class="sr sr-g3"><span class="sr-badge g3">G3</span><span class="sr-kp">Kp 7</span><span class="sr-vis">50°N+</span><span class="sr-fx">Voltage problems, intermittent GPS errors, satellite issues</span></div>
          <div class="sr sr-g4"><span class="sr-badge g4">G4</span><span class="sr-kp">Kp 8</span><span class="sr-vis">45°N+</span><span class="sr-fx">Widespread power outages, pipeline corrosion, HF radio blackouts</span></div>
          <div class="sr sr-g5"><span class="sr-badge g5">G5</span><span class="sr-kp">Kp 9</span><span class="sr-vis">40°N+</span><span class="sr-fx">Carrington-class: extreme power outages, months-long infrastructure damage</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- S + R Scales side by side -->
      <div class="scale-pair">
        <div class="scale-block card">
          <div class="scale-block-header">
            <span class="scale-letter-big">S</span>
            <div>
              <div class="scale-block-title">Solar Radiation Storms</div>
              <div class="scale-block-sub">Proton flux (≥10 MeV)</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="scale-rows">
            <div class="sr"><span class="sr-badge s1">S1</span><span class="sr-kp">10 pfu</span><span class="sr-fx">Minor HF radio degradation on sunlit side</span></div>
            <div class="sr"><span class="sr-badge s2">S2</span><span class="sr-kp">100 pfu</span><span class="sr-fx">Infrequent satellite single-event upsets</span></div>
            <div class="sr"><span class="sr-badge s3">S3</span><span class="sr-kp">1,000 pfu</span><span class="sr-fx">Radiation hazard to astronauts, memory errors</span></div>
            <div class="sr"><span class="sr-badge s4">S4</span><span class="sr-kp">10,000 pfu</span><span class="sr-fx">Star tracker issues, HF blackout on sunlit side</span></div>
            <div class="sr"><span class="sr-badge s5">S5</span><span class="sr-kp">100,000 pfu</span><span class="sr-fx">Complete HF blackout, severe astronaut radiation risk</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="scale-block card">
          <div class="scale-block-header">
            <span class="scale-letter-big">R</span>
            <div>
              <div class="scale-block-title">Radio Blackouts</div>
              <div class="scale-block-sub">X-ray flux from solar flares</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="scale-rows">
            <div class="sr"><span class="sr-badge r1">R1</span><span class="sr-kp">M1 flare</span><span class="sr-fx">Weak HF radio degradation, occasional loss</span></div>
            <div class="sr"><span class="sr-badge r2">R2</span><span class="sr-kp">M5 flare</span><span class="sr-fx">Limited blackout 10–15 min, nav signal errors</span></div>
            <div class="sr"><span class="sr-badge r3">R3</span><span class="sr-kp">X1 flare</span><span class="sr-fx">Wide HF blackout 1 hour, low-freq nav out</span></div>
            <div class="sr"><span class="sr-badge r4">R4</span><span class="sr-kp">X10 flare</span><span class="sr-fx">HF blackout on sunlit side 1–2 hours</span></div>
            <div class="sr"><span class="sr-badge r5">R5</span><span class="sr-kp">X20 flare</span><span class="sr-fx">Complete HF blackout on entire sunlit side for hours</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════
       BEST VIEWING LOCATIONS
  ══════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">BEST PLACES TO SEE THE AURORA</h2>
    <div class="places-grid">

      <div class="place-card">
        <div class="place-img">
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1531366936337-7c912a4589a7?auto=format&fit=crop&w=480&q=80"
               alt="Northern lights over Norwegian fjords" loading="lazy" />
        </div>
        <div class="place-body">
          <div class="place-top">
            <span class="flag">🇳🇴</span>
            <h3>Tromsø, Norway</h3>
            <span class="lat-badge">69.6°N</span>
          </div>
          <p>The world's undisputed aurora capital, sitting directly under the auroral oval. Dark polar nights from November to February. Excellent infrastructure — guided tours, snowmobile safaris, glass-roofed cabins. Minimum Kp needed: <strong>2</strong>.</p>
          <div class="place-tags">
            <span class="badge badge-green">BEST OVERALL</span>
            <span class="place-season">Oct – Mar</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="place-card">
        <div class="place-img">
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1494243762909-b498c7e7b548?auto=format&fit=crop&w=480&q=80"
               alt="Aurora over Icelandic landscape" loading="lazy" />
        </div>
        <div class="place-body">
          <div class="place-top">
            <span class="flag">🇮🇸</span>
            <h3>Iceland</h3>
            <span class="lat-badge">64–66°N</span>
          </div>
          <p>Vast dark landscapes, geothermal hot springs under the stars, black sand beaches lit by dancing light. Kp 3 is usually enough. The South Coast and Snæfellsnes Peninsula offer particularly dark skies. Minimum Kp: <strong>3</strong>.</p>
          <div class="place-tags">
            <span class="badge badge-green">HIGHLY RECOMMENDED</span>
            <span class="place-season">Sep – Apr</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="place-card">
        <div class="place-img">
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1566132127697-4524fea60007?auto=format&fit=crop&w=480&q=80"
               alt="Aurora over Finnish Lapland snow" loading="lazy" />
        </div>
        <div class="place-body">
          <div class="place-top">
            <span class="flag">🇫🇮</span>
            <h3>Finnish Lapland</h3>
            <span class="lat-badge">68–70°N</span>
          </div>
          <p>Saariselkä and Luosto average 200+ aurora nights per year. Magical winter scenery — snow-laden forests, frozen lakes, reindeer. Glass-roofed aurora cabins let you watch from bed. Minimum Kp: <strong>2</strong>.</p>
          <div class="place-tags">
            <span class="badge badge-green">GLASS CABINS</span>
            <span class="place-season">Nov – Mar</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="place-card">
        <div class="place-img">
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1517649763962-0c623066013b?auto=format&fit=crop&w=480&q=80"
               alt="Aurora borealis over Alaska mountains" loading="lazy" />
        </div>
        <div class="place-body">
          <div class="place-top">
            <span class="flag">🇺🇸</span>
            <h3>Fairbanks, Alaska</h3>
            <span class="lat-badge">64.8°N</span>
          </div>
          <p>Inside the auroral zone with extremely clear, cold, dry nights. Poker Flat Research Range is the world's largest land-based rocket range for aurora research. UAF Geophysical Institute provides excellent local forecasts. Minimum Kp: <strong>2</strong>.</p>
          <div class="place-tags">
            <span class="badge badge-yellow">RESEARCH HUB</span>
            <span class="place-season">Oct – Mar</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="place-card">
        <div class="place-img">
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1551244072-5d12893278bc?auto=format&fit=crop&w=480&q=80"
               alt="Aurora over Canadian wilderness" loading="lazy" />
        </div>
        <div class="place-body">
          <div class="place-top">
            <span class="flag">🇨🇦</span>
            <h3>Yukon, Canada</h3>
            <span class="lat-badge">60–65°N</span>
          </div>
          <p>Whitehorse sits directly under the auroral oval. Extraordinarily clear skies, very low humidity, and minimal light pollution. The Aurora Viewing Village at Takhini Hot Springs is a popular winter destination. Minimum Kp: <strong>2</strong>.</p>
          <div class="place-tags">
            <span class="badge badge-green">HIGHLY RECOMMENDED</span>
            <span class="place-season">Aug – Apr</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="place-card">
        <div class="place-img">
          <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1531366936337-7c912a4589a7?auto=format&fit=crop&w=480&q=80"
               alt="Aurora australis New Zealand southern lights" loading="lazy" />
        </div>
        <div class="place-body">
          <div class="place-top">
            <span class="flag">🇳🇿</span>
            <h3>Otago, New Zealand</h3>
            <span class="lat-badge">44–46°S</span>
          </div>
          <p>Southern Aurora (Aurora Australis) is visible from the South Island during moderate to strong storms. Lake Tekapo and the Mackenzie Basin have internationally-protected dark skies. Minimum Kp for visibility: <strong>5</strong>.</p>
          <div class="place-tags">
            <span class="badge badge-purple">AURORA AUSTRALIS</span>
            <span class="place-season">Mar – Sep</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════
       BEST TIME OF YEAR + MOON GUIDE
  ══════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">WHEN TO GO</h2>
    <div class="when-grid">

      <div class="season-card card">
        <div class="season-icon">🍂</div>
        <h3>Autumn (Sep – Nov)</h3>
        <p>Equinox seasons (around Sep 22 and Mar 20) see enhanced geomagnetic activity — Earth's magnetic field is more vulnerable at the equinoxes. September and October combine long dark nights with statistically elevated Kp. <strong>Best value</strong> aurora travel window.</p>
        <div class="season-rating"><span class="sr-dot sr-good"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-good"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-good"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-good"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-empty"></span></div>
      </div>

      <div class="season-card card">
        <div class="season-icon">❄️</div>
        <h3>Winter (Dec – Feb)</h3>
        <p>Maximum darkness — polar nights above 67°N mean up to 24 hours of darkness per day. Cold air is dry and clear. Fewer clouds than autumn. The tradeoff: extremely cold temperatures and shorter windows for comfortable outdoor viewing.</p>
        <div class="season-rating"><span class="sr-dot sr-good"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-good"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-good"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-good"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-good"></span></div>
      </div>

      <div class="season-card card">
        <div class="season-icon">🌸</div>
        <h3>Spring (Mar – Apr)</h3>
        <p>Second equinox peak — March equinox brings statistically the highest average Kp of the year. Longer nights than autumn in the northern hemisphere but still dark enough. Temperatures are milder. <strong>April often sees strong G2–G3 storms.</strong></p>
        <div class="season-rating"><span class="sr-dot sr-good"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-good"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-good"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-good"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-empty"></span></div>
      </div>

      <div class="season-card card">
        <div class="season-icon">☀️</div>
        <h3>Summer (Jun – Aug)</h3>
        <p>Midnight sun above the Arctic Circle means the sky never gets truly dark. Aurora still occurs — the magnetosphere is active — but it's invisible in the bright sky. The exception: powerful G4–G5 storms can produce aurora visible even in twilight.</p>
        <div class="season-rating"><span class="sr-dot sr-empty"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-empty"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-empty"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-empty"></span><span class="sr-dot sr-empty"></span></div>
      </div>

    </div>

    <div class="moon-guide card">
