  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS</h2>
    <div class="faq-grid">

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-q">What Kp level do I need to see the aurora?</summary>
        <div class="faq-a">
          <p>It depends on your latitude. At 65–70°N (Tromsø, Lapland, Alaska), Kp 2–3 is often enough for a good display. At 55–60°N (Scotland, southern Norway, southern Canada), you need Kp 5+. In central Europe or the northern United States, Kp 7 or higher is typically required. During the historic G5 storm of May 2024, aurora was visible as far south as Florida and the Canary Islands — that required Kp 9.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-q">Why does southward Bz produce aurora?</summary>
        <div class="faq-a">
          <p>When the interplanetary magnetic field (IMF) Bz component points south, it aligns anti-parallel with Earth's northward-pointing magnetic field at the dayside magnetopause. This allows magnetic reconnection — where opposing field lines break and reconnect, releasing enormous energy. This opens a portal for solar wind particles to enter the magnetosphere and flow toward the polar regions, driving aurora. The more negative Bz is, the more intense the reconnection and the stronger the aurora.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-q">Why does aurora happen mostly around midnight?</summary>
        <div class="faq-a">
          <p>The magnetospheric tail — the night side of Earth's magnetic field, stretched by solar wind pressure — stores energy during the day and releases it explosively in events called substorms, typically peaking around local midnight. Substorm onset triggers rapid brightening of the aurora oval, producing the most dynamic and colourful displays. The hours of 10pm–2am local time consistently produce the best aurora, though displays can occur any time the sky is dark.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-q">Can I see aurora with the naked eye?</summary>
        <div class="faq-a">
          <p>Yes — moderate to strong events (Kp 5+) are clearly visible with the naked eye from mid-to-high latitudes as green curtains, arcs, or rays. Weaker displays (Kp 2–4) are often visible to the dark-adapted eye as a faint greenish glow on the horizon, but cameras detect it more easily because camera sensors are more sensitive to the 557.7 nm green wavelength. Always take a test photo before assuming there's nothing to see — you might be surprised.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-q">Are we currently in a good period for aurora?</summary>
        <div class="faq-a">
          <p>Yes — Solar Cycle 25 peaked around mid-2025, making 2024–2026 the best aurora-viewing window in over a decade. The May 2024 G5 storm (the strongest since the Halloween Storm of 2003) produced aurora visible worldwide and dramatically demonstrated the power of this solar maximum. Activity typically remains elevated for 1–2 years around the peak before declining toward solar minimum around 2030.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-q">How far in advance can aurora be forecast?</summary>
        <div class="faq-a">
          <p>Reliable aurora forecasting is limited to 1–4 days. When a CME is observed leaving the Sun, scientists can predict its Earth-arrival time within ±6 hours. Once the solar wind reaches the DSCOVR satellite at the L1 Lagrange point (1.5 million km from Earth), we have 15–60 minutes of real-time warning before it hits. Kp forecasts for the next 3 hours are highly reliable; 24-hour forecasts are moderately reliable; beyond 3 days is largely speculative. The best strategy: watch NOAA alerts and stay flexible.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-q">What is STEVE and how is it different from aurora?</summary>
        <div class="faq-a">
          <p>STEVE (Strong Thermal Emission Velocity Enhancement) appears as a narrow, purple-white or mauve ribbon running east-west across the sky, distinct from the aurora's north-south oriented curtains. It was formally identified and named by citizen scientists in 2016. Unlike aurora — which is caused by energetic particle precipitation — STEVE is caused by a hot, fast-moving stream of ions in the sub-auroral ionosphere at lower latitudes. It often appears alongside traditional aurora but is a separate optical phenomenon.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary class="faq-q">What is hemispheric power and why does it matter?</summary>
        <div class="faq-a">
          <p>Hemispheric Power (HP) is the total power deposited into the polar atmosphere by aurora-causing particles, measured in gigawatts. NOAA estimates it in real-time using satellite data. HP below 30 GW indicates quiet conditions; 30–100 GW is active; above 100 GW indicates strong storm conditions. Unlike Kp (which is updated every 3 hours), HP is derived from real-time measurements and can show rapidly changing aurora intensity within minutes, making it a useful supplementary metric alongside Kp and Bz.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

    </div>
  </section>

